<!-- Pain Points -->
<section class="section bg-cream">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header centered">
            <span class="section-eyebrow">Sound Familiar?</span>
            <h2>The Problems Every Landscape Manager Knows</h2>
            <p>These aren't rare edge cases — they're the everyday frustrations drip irrigation was built to solve.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="three-col-grid">
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">💸</div>
                <h3>Water Bills That Never Stop Climbing</h3>
                <p>Spray and rotor systems apply water indiscriminately — over sidewalks, hardscaping, and compacted areas where it runs straight off. You're paying for water that never reaches a root zone.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Drip delivers only to root zones — nothing wasted on pavement or air.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">🚫</div>
                <h3>Water Restrictions Threatening Your Contracts</h3>
                <p>Municipal mandates are limiting irrigation days and windows. Spray systems can't comply and still keep landscapes alive in summer heat. You're forced to choose between compliance and dead plants.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Drip systems often qualify for restrictions exemptions and use up to 50% less water while maintaining the same plant health.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">🍄</div>
                <h3>Disease from Wet Foliage</h3>
                <p>Overhead watering keeps leaves and crowns chronically wet — creating ideal conditions for fungal disease, mold, and root rot that cost real money in plant replacement and labor.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Drip keeps water at the root zone, not on foliage — dramatically reducing fungal pressure and plant loss.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">⚠️</div>
                <h3>Liability from Overspray onto Hardscapes</h3>
                <p>Overspray onto walkways, driveways, and roads creates slip hazards and staining. In commercial settings that's real liability exposure — and insurers are taking notice.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Subsurface and surface drip stays below the canopy — no runoff, no hazards, no complaints.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">⏰</div>
                <h3>Labor Drain from Constant Repairs</h3>
                <p>Broken heads, clogged nozzles, and uneven coverage mean crews are constantly troubleshooting instead of maintaining. Spray heads get hit by mowers, pedestrians, and vehicles every week.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ Low-profile drip systems are nearly invisible, highly durable, and require far less maintenance than spray or rotor systems.</div>
            </div>
            <div class="pain-card">
                <div class="pain-icon">📋</div>
                <h3>LEED and Sustainability Requirements</h3>
                <p>Developers and property owners increasingly require LEED-compliant water management. Standard spray irrigation doesn't earn points — and you're the one who has to explain it to a client.</p>
                <div class="pain-solution">✓ DripSmart systems are LEED credit compatible and come with the documentation needed for certification.</div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

